In [[Greek mythology]], '''Amphimachus''' ({{IPAc-en|æ|m|ˈ|f|ɪ|m|ə|k|ə|s}}; [[Ancient Greek]]: Ἀμφίμαχος derived from ἀμφί ''amphi'' "on both sides, in all directions, surrounding" and μαχη ''mache'' "battle") was a name attributed to multiple individuals. * [[Amphimachus (son of Cteatus)|Amphimachus]], son of [[Eurytus and Cteatus|Cteatus]] and [[Theronice]].<ref name=":02">Homer. ''The Iliad'', [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HomerIliad13.html 13.169]</ref> * [[Amphimachus (son of Nomion)|Amphimachus]], son of Nomion.<ref name=":0">Homer. ''The Iliad'', [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HomerIliad2.html 2.866]</ref> * [[Amphimachus (son of Electryon)|Amphimachus]], son of [[Electryon]] and [[Anaxo]].<ref>Apollodorus. ''The Library'', [http://www.theoi.com/Text/Apollodorus2.html 2.4.6]</ref> *[[Amphimachus (king of Elis)|Amphimachus]], son of [[Polyxenus]] and king of [[Elis]].<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], Description of Greece, [http://www.theoi.com/Text/Pausanias5A.html 5. 3. 4 - 5]</ref> * Amphimachus, one of the [[suitors of Penelope]] from [[Dulichium]]. He was ultimately killed by [[Odysseus]].<ref name=":1" /> * Amphimachus, also one of the suitors of [[Penelope]] from [[Ithaca]]. He too was ultimately killed by Odysseus.<ref name=":1">Apollodorus, Bibliotheca, Epitome of Book 4, [http://www.theoi.com/Text/ApollodorusE.html#7 7. 26 - 33]</ref> * Amphimachus, a Greek warrior in the [[Trojan War]], and one of the men hidden inside the [[Trojan horse]].<ref>Quintus Smyrnaeus. ''The Fall of Troy'', [http://www.theoi.com/Text/QuintusSmyrnaeus12.html 12.337]</ref>
