The International Religious Freedom Report 2008, submitted by the [[United States Department of State]] to Congress as required by the [[International Religious Freedom Act of 1998]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Preface: International Religious Freedom Report 2008|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2008/108349.htm|publisher=United States Department of State|accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref> provides the following summary of religious affiliation in Barbados:<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbados: International Religious Freedom Report 2008|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2008/108513.htm|publisher=United States Department of State|accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref>
{{quote|text=According to the 2000 official census, more than 95 percent of the population of [[Barbados]] is considered [[Christianity|Christian]], although persons may not be active in any particular [[Christian denomination|denomination]].
[[Anglicanism]] constitutes the largest religious group, with 70,000 members; an estimated 67 percent are active. It is represented by the [[Church in the Province of the West Indies]], within which the island belongs to the [[Diocese of Barbados]]. The next largest group is the [[Seventh-day Adventists]], numbering 16,000 members, 10,000 of whom are active. There are 11,000 [[Roman Catholics]]; an estimated 20 percent are active. [[Pentecostals]] number 7,000; more than 50 percent are active. [[Methodists#Caribbean|Methodists]] number 5,000, according to church officials, although many more claimed Methodist affiliation in the previous official census; an estimated 60 percent are active. There are 2,500 members of [[Jehovah's Witnesses]]; more than 95 percent are active. [[Baptists]], [[Moravian Church|Moravians]], and members of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (Mormons) are present in small numbers.
The number of non-Christians is small. There are 4,000 [[Islam in Barbados|Muslims]], most of whom are immigrants or descendants of [[Indo-Caribbean|Indian immigrants]] from the [[India]]n [[States of India|state]] of [[Gujarat]]. There are three mosques and an Islamic centre. Other religious groups include Rastafarians, [[Hinduism|Hindus]], [[Buddhism|Buddhists]], and members of the [[Baha'i Faith]].}}
